```suggestion
theorem setOf_inj {p q : Î± â†’ Prop} : { x | p x } = { x | q x } â†” p = q := rfl
```

```suggestion
theorem setOf_mem_empty : { x | x âˆˆ ([] : List Î±) } = âˆ… := by
```

```suggestion
theorem setOf_mem_eq_empty_iff {l : List Î±} : { x | x âˆˆ l } = âˆ… â†” l = [] := by
```

```suggestion
theorem setOf_eq_singleton_iff_of_nodup (H : Nodup l) {a : Î±} [DecidableEq Î±]
```
I think a better theorem here is that converting a list to a set in this way is InjOn the set of lists satisfying l.Nodup, from which this follows trivially
I used permutations instead of `InjOn`, but it should still have the right idea.

Colons go on the right:
```suggestion
theorem setOf_nodup_perm (l : List Î±) (H : l.Nodup) [DecidableEq Î±] :
    l.finite_toSet.toFinset.toList.Perm l := by
```
The theorem name doesn't indicate at all that a list is involved. Maybe `setOf_mem_list_eq_singleton` optionally followed by `_iff` and/or `_of_nodup`.
Maybe `l` can be implicit
Do you actually need this? If you do, it might be better as an instance `Fintype {x // p x} â†’ Fintype {x | p x}`?
It's necessary for the `toFinite_toFinset` call in `setOf_mem_list_eq_singleton_of_nodup`. I changed it to use an implicit instance.
This instance worries me a little, and might be worth asking Zulip about (apologies if I missed a previous conversation).
[It was discussed a little here](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20488#discussion_r1910367396).
I think this is almost the same as [`List.toFinset_toList`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Finset/Dedup.html#List.toFinset_toList)?
Indeed, it seems the missing piece is `{x | x âˆˆ l}.toFinset = l.toFinset`, which would be a good simp lemma.
Why are we writing `{x | x âˆˆ l}` to begin with? We could be writing `â†‘l.toFinset` directly.

> `â†‘l.toFinset` directly.

Only with `DecidableEq`.
You can state this result without `DecidableEq Î±` and instead start the proof with `classical`, which should hopefully make the weird `Fintype {x | x âˆˆ l}` instance unnecessary.
I opted not to do this, as inferring the non-simp-normal `Finite` instance was still necessary even with classical.
I think these two are orthogonal problems. Even if the `Fintype` weirdness persists, omitting `DecidableEq` in theorems that don't need it will save future users from problems later down the line.
Yes `DecidableEq` should be removed from both the statements here as it is not needed to make the statement typecheck. As Violeta says, the proofs should start `classical`.

`haveI` is a Lean 3-ism; also, you should generally use `let` for data.
```suggestion
  let _ : Fintype {x | x âˆˆ l} := inferInstanceAs (Fintype { x // x âˆˆ l })
```

```suggestion
-- (as the proper simp-normal form of `â†‘ { x | p x }` is `{ x // p x }`)
```

This would cause `simp` do to the following:
```
example : {x : â„ | x ^ 2 = 3} = {x : â„ | x ^ 4 = 9 } := by
  simp
  -- âŠ¢ (fun x â†¦ x ^ 2 = 3) = fun x â†¦ x ^ 4 = 9
```
Is this desirable?
I have to agree, this seems like quite a ludicrous simp lemma. It can definitely be useful as a simp lemma, but it shouldn't be tagged as one.
I don't really see the point of this lemma
I see the point of this lemma iff it's simp
This looks like it's provable without material on finiteness. You should also be able to generalise it to say l = replicate n a for some n > 0 without the nodup assumption

```
theorem setOf_mem_list_eq_replicate {l : List Î±} {a : Î±} :
    { x | x âˆˆ l } = {a} â†” âˆƒ n > 0, l = List.replicate n a := by
  simpa +contextual [Set.ext_iff, iff_iff_implies_and_implies, forall_and, List.eq_replicate_iff,
    List.length_pos_iff_exists_mem] using âŸ¨fun _ _ â†¦ âŸ¨_, â€¹_â€ºâŸ©, fun x hx h â†¦ h _ hx â–¸ hxâŸ©

theorem setOf_mem_list_eq_singleton_of_nodup {l : List Î±} (H : l.Nodup) {a : Î±} :
    { x | x âˆˆ l } = {a} â†” l = [a] := by
  constructor
  Â· rw [setOf_mem_list_eq_replicate]
    rintro âŸ¨n, hn, rflâŸ©
    simp only [List.nodup_replicate] at H
    simp [show n = 1 by omega]
  Â· rintro rfl
    simp
```
here's what I mean - these things should be true just from list and set things, not finite set things
